\f0\b\fs28 \cf0 Example Template for IEP Goals\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf0 This template from Dr. Destiny Huff provides a practical structure for drafting S.M.A.R.T., neuroaffirming goals.\
By [date \'96 typically this is a year from the IEP goal date], the learner [insert learner's name] will [skill \'96 what skill is to be developed, what action is the learner supposed to do] when [trigger -what triggers the situation or during what time does the skill need to occur] using [supports \'96 what supports will help the learner \'96 executive functioning, sensory, communication, motor, staff] in [how often will the learner demonstrate the skill \'96 4 out of 5, 80% of the time, daily, etc.] as evidenced by [Data Collection - how will data be collected, i.e. teacher observation, log sheet, learner self-report, testing, etc.].\
Once appropriate goals are set, they must be supported by a similarly nuanced and supportive Behavior Intervention Plan.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs36 \cf0 6.0 Developing a Proactive and Supportive Behavior Intervention Plan (BIP)\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf0 For a PDA student, a Behavior Intervention Plan (BIP) should not be viewed as a disciplinary tool, but as a supportive, proactive roadmap for understanding and reducing nervous system distress. A PDA-affirming BIP is overwhelmingly focused on preventative strategies\'97modifying the environment, instruction, and communication to prevent the activation of the student's threat response in the first place. It is a plan for the adults in the room, guiding them on how to create safety, build trust, and respond with co-regulation when the student's survival brain takes over.\
The following components, modeled after a best-practice example, outline the structure of a supportive BIP.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs28 \cf0 Redefining Target Behaviors and Hypothesizing Function\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf0 First, the BIP must redefine "target behaviors" (e.g., vocal dysregulation, physical aggression, property misuse) not as willful acts of defiance, but as expressions of a nervous system in distress. The function of these behaviors is hypothesized to be a combination of avoiding overwhelming tasks, seeking attention for co-regulation, and attempting to self-regulate a panicked sensory system. This reframing is a critical first step for the entire team.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs28 \cf0 Proactive Environmental and Instructional Strategies\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf0 This is the core of the BIP. The goal is to create an environment so accommodating that the student can remain 
\f0\b HRE (Happy, Relaxed, and Engaged)
\f1\b0 .\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls7\ilvl0
\f0\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Fill the environment
\f1\b0  with preferred items (e.g., MagnaTiles, bracelet kits, electronics) that are readily available without needing to be "earned."\
\ls7\ilvl0
\f0\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Provide choice and autonomy
\f1\b0  in activities, seating, and movement throughout the day.\
\ls7\ilvl0
\f0\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Establish a calming area
\f1\b0  or safe space the student can access at any time.\
\ls7\ilvl0
\f0\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Use Declarative Language
\f1\b0  consistently to reduce the perception of demands. Examples include: "I wonder what would happen if we tried..." or "I'm feeling frustrated. I think I'll take a walk."\
\ls7\ilvl0
\f0\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Use a visual schedule flexibly
\f1\b0 , as a guide to create predictability, not as a rigid set of expectations to follow.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs28 \cf0 Teaching Replacement Behaviors\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf0 Instead of punishing distress behaviors, the BIP focuses on explicitly teaching and reinforcing functional communication. The student is taught to:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls8\ilvl0\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Request a break or "more time please."\
\ls8\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Request help or state, "I don't want to do this right now."\
\ls8\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Use a chewy or gum as an alternative to biting.\
\ls8\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Request others to stop an activity or be quiet.\
\ls8\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 All appropriate communicative requests should be honored immediately to reinforce their use.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs28 \cf0 Positive Supports and Natural Motivators\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf0 Traditional reward systems like token boards are avoided as they create anxiety and a sense of demand. Instead, support is relational and intrinsic.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls9\ilvl0
\f0\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Pairing:
\f1\b0  Staff must dedicate time daily to building a positive relationship with the student. The goal is to show the student that "his world is more fun with you than without you!" This involves a deliberate, child-led process of building relational safety, such as passively following their lead and engaging in parallel play until the student initiates interaction.\
\ls9\ilvl0
\f0\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Natural Rewards:
\f1\b0  Reinforcement is provided naturally. For example, "Wow, you finished that, now you have free choice time until your friends finish!"\
\ls9\ilvl0
\f0\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Behavior-specific praise
\f1\b0  is used authentically, focusing on the effort or outcome (e.g., "Your letter M looks amazing").\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs28 \cf0 Reactive De-escalation Strategies\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf0 When the student's threat response is activated, the focus shifts entirely to co-regulation and ensuring safety.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls10\ilvl0
\f0\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Remain Calm and Neutral:
\f1\b0  The adult's primary job is to be the calm in the storm.\
\ls10\ilvl0
\f0\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Do Not Talk About the Behavior:
\f1\b0  Instead, empathize with the student's feelings ("I'm so sorry today is hard," or "I wish I knew what you needed right now.").\
\ls10\ilvl0
\f0\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Block and Disengage:
\f1\b0  If aggression occurs, calmly block for safety and remove others from the immediate area if necessary.\
\ls10\ilvl0
\f0\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Give Space:
\f1\b0  Use declarative language and provide as much physical space as the student needs to feel safe.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs28 \cf0 Crisis Planning\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf0 A crisis plan is a last resort, used only when there is an immediate threat to safety. Crucially, given the potential for trauma, it must prioritize de-escalation over restraint.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls11\ilvl0\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 If high rates of aggression or self-injury persist, parents are to be called immediately.\
\ls11\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 The plan must explicitly state that parents will be notified and given the option to pick the student up from school 
\f2\i before
\f1\i0  a decision for physical management is made. This acknowledges the significant trauma that restraint can cause and respects the family's role in crisis intervention, as physical management will harm his ability to remain at school long-term and hurt relationships he has formed with staff.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 This guide began by calling for a foundational shift in perspective. The journey from understanding the intricacies of the PDA nervous system to crafting a supportive Behavior Intervention Plan is not linear but a continuous loop of learning, adapting, and prioritizing the child's felt safety above all else. A successful IEP for a PDA student is a living document, built on a foundation of trust, flexibility, and a deep, compassionate understanding of the child's unique neurology. This is not just about writing a better IEP; it is about fundamentally changing the adult-child dynamic to one of trust and co-regulation, which is the only environment where a PDA child can truly build authentic skills, foster a sense of agency, and thrive.\
}